                "DEFINITION & SCOPE",
                "Branch of Environmental Engineering dealing with safe, adequate, and potable water supply for domestic, industrial, and public use. Ensures protection of public health and meets Nepal drinking water standards (NDWQS).",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "POLLUTANTS IN DRINKING WATER",
                "Sources: Natural (Minerals, organic matter), Domestic (Sewage, detergents), Industrial (Heavy metals, chemicals), Agricultural (Fertilizers, pesticides)\nTypes: Physical (Turbidity, color, taste, odor), Chemical (Hardness, fluoride, nitrate, heavy metals), Biological (Bacteria, viruses, protozoa)\nEffects: Health hazards (Diarrhea, cholera, fluorosis), Aesthetic (Bad taste, color, odor), Operational (Scaling in pipes, corrosion)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "SOURCES OF WATER",
                "1 Surface water: Rivers, lakes, reservoirs\n2 Groundwater: Wells, tube wells, springs\n3 Other sources: Rainwater harvesting, desalination\nNepal relevance: Rivers and springs main sources; groundwater common in rural areas.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "CHARACTERISTICS OF WATER",
                "Physical: Color, taste, odor, turbidity, temperature\nChemical: pH (6.5–8.5), hardness, fluoride (<1.5 mg/L), nitrate (<45 mg/L)\nBiological: Total coliform < 0 per 100 mL\nNDWQS & WHO guidelines for safe water.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "WATER DEMAND & QUANTITY",
                "Types of demand: Domestic, industrial, commercial, firefighting, public use\nPer capita demand: 135–150 lpcd (urban), 70–100 lpcd (rural)\nEstimation of future population: Exponential growth\nDesign period: 20–25 years urban, 15–20 years rural",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "PRESENT STATUS & ISSUES",
                "Urban Nepal: Leakage, contamination, intermittent supply\nRural Nepal: Lack of piped water, reliance on wells and springs\nCommon issues: Waterborne diseases, unsustainable sources, inequitable distribution, poor maintenance",
                ""
