      "sections": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Wastewater Fundamentals",
          "table": {
            "header": ["SUB-TOPIC", "SHORT DESCRIPTION / NOTES", "EXTRA"],
            "rows": [
              [
                "DEFINITION & SCOPE",
                "Wastewater is water from domestic, industrial, and storm sources containing pollutants that require treatment before disposal or reuse. Ensures public health protection and environmental safety.",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "SOURCES OF WASTEWATER",
                "1 Domestic: Toilets, kitchens, bathrooms\n2 Industrial: Factories, breweries, tanneries, paper mills\n3 Stormwater / Surface runoff: Carries debris, chemicals\n4 Combined sewer systems in urban Nepal — mixture of domestic + stormwater",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "NATURE & CHARACTERISTICS",
                "Physical: Color, temperature, turbidity, suspended solids\nChemical: BOD, COD, pH, nutrients (N, P), heavy metals\nBiological: Coliforms, pathogens\nKey parameters:\nBOD₅: Amount of oxygen consumed in 5 days (mg/L)\nCOD: Total oxygen demand by chemical oxidation (mg/L)\nAerobic decomposition: Organic matter oxidized by bacteria → CO₂ + H₂O\nAnaerobic decomposition: Organic matter decomposed without oxygen → CH₄ + CO₂ + H₂S",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "PHYSICAL TREATMENT",
                "1 Screening: Removes large debris; bar screens or mesh screens\n2 Grit Chamber: Removes sand, grit; prevents abrasion\n3 Gas Chamber / Equalization Tank: Balances flow and prevents shock loads\n4 Mixing: Ensures uniform chemical addition\n5 Sedimentation / Primary Clarifier: Settling of suspended solids\n6 Flocculation / Coagulation: Chemicals like alum added; promotes aggregation\n7 Floatation / DAF: Removes light solids using air bubbles",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "CHEMICAL TREATMENT",
                "1 Chemical Precipitation: Removes phosphates, heavy metals; e.g., lime, alum\n2 Absorption: Pollutants adhere to activated carbon\n3 Ion Exchange: Removes hardness, heavy metals\n4 Electrolysis / Electrocoagulation: Electrical current precipitates contaminants",
                ""
              ]
            ]
          }
        },
