      "title": "Chapter 4: Biological Treatment & Sludge Management",
      "sections": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "level": 3,
          "title": "Biological Treatment Processes",
          "table": {
            "header": ["SUB-TOPIC", "SHORT DESCRIPTION / NOTES", "EXTRA"],
            "rows": [
              [
                "BIOLOGICAL TREATMENT – OVERVIEW",
                "Uses microorganisms to remove organic matter (BOD, COD) from wastewater.\nTypes: Aerobic (Requires oxygen, faster degradation), Anaerobic (Without oxygen, produces methane)",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "AEROBIC PROCESS",
                "Microorganisms oxidize organic matter → CO₂ + H₂O\nCommon units: Activated Sludge Process, Trickling Filter, Aerated Lagoon, Oxidation Ditch",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "ACTIVATED SLUDGE PROCESS (ASP)",
                "Suspended growth process; microorganisms in aeration tank\nWastewater mixed with return sludge\nDesign parameters: HRT = V/Q, SRT = XV/Q_wX_w\nOxygen requirement: O₂ = 1.42 × (BOD_i - BOD_f) kg/day",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "TRICKLING FILTER",
                "Wastewater trickled over biological media colonized by biofilm\nOrganic removal efficiency: 70–90%\nOrganic loading rate = BOD applied / Area / day",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "AERATED LAGOONS / OXIDATION PONDS",
                "Large shallow ponds; mechanical aeration or natural aeration\nHydraulic retention time: 3–10 days\nRemoval efficiency: 50–90% depending on depth, temperature",
                ""
              ],
              [
                "OXIDATION DITCH",
                "Continuous loop channel, aeration provided via diffusers\nHRT: 12–24 h\nSuitable for small-medium towns in Nepal",
                ""
              ],
              ["SLUDGE DRYING", "Reduces moisture by sun or mechanical drying; reduces volume", ""],
